Yes, this pattern can absolutely be achieved directly within your Go application using the AWS SDK for Go v2.

While AWS Step Functions handle this using a Task state with a polling or event-driven backoff loop behind the scenes, you can replicate this behavior in Go by utilizing two primary tools from the SDK:

Asynchronous Lambda Invocation (using InvocationTypeEvent) so the Go application doesn't block on a long-running Lambda process.

Built-in SDK Waiters or a custom polling loop with backoff to query the status of the RDS resource until it transitions to AVAILABLE.

Here is how you can implement this architecture in Go.

🏗️ Architecture Design Pattern
Instead of invoking the Lambda synchronously (RequestResponse), you fire it asynchronously (Event). The Lambda triggers the creation of the RDS Blue/Green deployment and exits immediately. Your Go process then takes over the heavy lifting of polling the RDS API until the deployment is ready.

Below is the complete implementation utilizing the AWS SDK for Go v2. It includes a custom polling function with exponential backoff to monitor the RDS Blue/Green deployment status.

package main

import (
  "context"
  "encoding/json"
  "errors"
  "fmt"
  "log"
  "time"

  "github.com/aws/aws-sdk-go-v2/aws"
  "github.com/aws/aws-sdk-go-v2/config"
  "github.com/aws/aws-sdk-go-v2/service/lambda"
  "github.com/aws/aws-sdk-go-v2/service/lambda/types"
  "github.com/aws/aws-sdk-go-v2/service/rds"
)

type DeploymentPayload struct {
  DeploymentName string `json:"deploymentName"`
  SourceDBArn    string `json:"sourceDbArn"`
  TargetVersion  string `json:"targetVersion"`
}

func main() {
  ctx := context.TODO()
  
  // Initialize AWS Configuration
  cfg, err := config.LoadDefaultConfig(ctx)
  if err != nil {
    log.Fatalf("failed to load SDK config: %v", err)
  }

  lambdaClient := lambda.NewFromConfig(cfg)
  rdsClient := rds.NewFromConfig(cfg)

  deploymentName := "pg-upgrade-deployment"
  
  // 1. Prepare payload for the automation Lambda
  payload := DeploymentPayload{
    DeploymentName: deploymentName,
    SourceDBArn:    "arn:aws:rds:us-east-1:123456789012:db:production-postgres",
    TargetVersion:  "17.1",
  }
  
  payloadBytes, _ := json.Marshal(payload)

  // 2. Invoke Lambda Asynchronously (Event Type)
  fmt.Println("🚀 Triggering Lambda function to initiate Blue/Green environment...")
  _, err = lambdaClient.Invoke(ctx, &lambda.InvokeInput{
    FunctionName:   aws.String("InitiateBlueGreenDeploymentLambda"),
    InvocationType: types.InvocationTypeEvent, // Asynchronous execution
    Payload:        payloadBytes,
  })
  if err != nil {
    log.Fatalf("Failed to invoke Lambda: %v", err)
  }
  fmt.Println("✅ Lambda invoked successfully. Handing off monitoring to the Go routine.")

  // 3. Poll the RDS Resource state until it is available
  fmt.Printf("⏳ Polling RDS Blue/Green deployment '%s' status...\n", deploymentName)
  err = waitForBlueGreenDeployment(ctx, rdsClient, deploymentName, 30*time.Minute)
  if err != nil {
    log.Fatalf("❌ Error or timeout during deployment: %v", err)
  }

  fmt.Println("🎉 Success! The Blue/Green deployment is active and ready for switchover.")
}

// waitForBlueGreenDeployment blocks until the RDS B/G deployment status is 'AVAILABLE'
func waitForBlueGreenDeployment(ctx context.Context, client *rds.Client, deploymentID string, timeout time.Duration) error {
  ctx, cancel := context.WithTimeout(ctx, timeout)
  defer cancel()

  // Configure polling interval rules
  baseDelay := 15 * time.Second
  maxDelay := 2 * time.Minute
  currentDelay := baseDelay

  for {
    select {
    case <-ctx.Done():
      return errors.New("polling timed out before deployment reached available state")
    default:
      // Query the specific Blue/Green deployment status
      output, err := client.DescribeBlueGreenDeployments(ctx, &rds.DescribeBlueGreenDeploymentsInput{
        BlueGreenDeploymentIdentifier: aws.String(deploymentID),
      })
      if err != nil {
        fmt.Printf("⚠️ Warning: Error calling DescribeBlueGreenDeployments: %v. Retrying...\n", err)
        goto WaitPhase
      }

      if len(output.BlueGreenDeployments) == 0 {
        fmt.Println("⚠️ Target deployment not found yet. It might still be provisioning via Lambda...")
        goto WaitPhase
      }

      // Capture the current status from the target deployment metadata
      status := *output.BlueGreenDeployments[0].Status
      fmt.Printf("[%s] Current Status: %s\n", time.Now().Format("15:04:05"), status)

      switch status {
      case "AVAILABLE", "PROVISIONING_COMPLETE": 
        return nil
      case "FAILED", "INSUFFICIENT_CAPACITY":
        return fmt.Errorf("deployment entered a critical failure state: %s", status)
      }

    WaitPhase:
      // Execute backoff sleep
      time.Sleep(currentDelay)
      
      // Increment delay exponentially up to max boundary
      currentDelay *= 2
      if currentDelay > maxDelay {
        currentDelay = maxDelay
      }
    }
  }
}

types.InvocationTypeEvent: Essential for this architecture. When using this type, AWS accepts the payload immediately, registers an HTTP 202 status, and breaks the network connection so your web application frontend doesn't hang waiting for the Lambda execution timeline.

Context Timeouts: Database environment configurations can take 15 to 45 minutes to stand up. Utilizing context.WithTimeout allows your application to fail gracefully if it exceeds your infrastructure SLA limits rather than looping endlessly.

Exponential Backoff: Instead of hitting the RDS API continuously every second (which will trigger AWS API Rate Limiting / throttling), the loop multiplies the wait interval progressively until it reaches a stable 2-minute check cycle.
